1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bd7 (6...
cxd4 {was the correct move order.} 7. O-O ({or} 7. cxd4)) 7. dxc5 $3 {
Nimzowitsch gives two exclamation marks to this move. I think it is too much,
but still, White can transpose to a quite comfortable structure.} Bxc5 8. O-O
f6 9. b4 $1 Be7 10. Bf4 fxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Nf6 (12... Bf6 13. Qh5+ g6
14. Bxg6+ hxg6 15. Qxg6+ Ke7 16. Bxf6+ Nxf6 17. Qg7+ $18) 13. Nd2 (13. Qc2 O-O
$1) 13... O-O 14. Nf3 $1 $14 {White has better structure and full control of
the e5 and d4 squares.} Bd6 15. Qe2 (15. Bd4) 15... Rac8 16. Bd4 Qc7 17. Ne5
Be8 18. Rae1 {a picturesque position. All of White's pieces are very active
and now it's time to convert the potential energy into something concrete.}
Bxe5 (18... Ne4 $1 {was the only chance}) 19. Bxe5 Qc6 20. Bd4 $1 Bd7 21. Qc2
Rf7 22. Re3 b6 23. Rg3 Kh8 24. Bxh7 $1 {In such active position is very
natural to find some concrete solution} e5 (24... Nxh7 25. Qg6 $18) 25. Bg6 $18
Re7 26. Re1 Qd6 27. Be3 d4 28. Bg5 Rxc3 29. Rxc3 dxc3 30. Qxc3 Kg8 31. a3 Kf8
32. Bh4 Be8 33. Bf5 Qd4 34. Qxd4 exd4 35. Rxe7 Kxe7 36. Bd3 Kd6 37. Bxf6 gxf6
38. Kf1 Bc6 39. h4 1-0

