1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Nc6 {This move can be
considered inaccurate because it gives White the option to change the
structure.} 7. dxc5 $5 Bxc5 8. O-O {White gets a very comfortable position.
Now his idea is to secure the safety of the e5 pawn, later occupy the
d4-square by the knight and then organize an attack against Black's king. With
the pawn alive on e5, Black's king will always feel very uncomfortable on the
kingside. Typical sheme for development here is Nd2-b3, Qe2, Bf4, Re1,
followed by h4-Ng5 or just Ng5.} Qc7 9. Re1 Nge7 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Nb3 Bb6 12.
Qe2 O-O 13. Nbd4 a6 14. h4 $1 {The knight on "g6" is usually met by this
advance.} f6 15. Bxg6 {securing full control of the e5-square.} hxg6 16. Bf4
Nxd4 17. Nxd4 (17. cxd4 {keeping the knight on the board was better. Now White
can try to organize an attack on the weakened kingside.}) 17... Bxd4 18. cxd4
f5 19. Rac1 (19. h5 {opening the h-file looks more logical.}) 19... Qa5 20. Qe3
Rfc8 21. Qg3 Kf7 22. Qb3 Bb5 23. a3 Qa4 24. Qe3 Rc2 (24... Be8 {White is still
better, but Black's position looks extremely solid.}) 25. Rxc2 Qxc2 26. Rc1
Qxb2 27. Rc7+ Kg8 28. Qg3 (28. Bh6 $1 gxh6 29. Qxh6 {with mate to follow})
28... Be8 29. h5 Qb6 30. Re7 Qxd4 31. Kh2 Qc5 32. Qh4 Rc8 33. h6 gxh6 34. Qf6
1-0

