1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O
a5 9. Qe2 Nge7 10. Nbd2 a4 {Black stops Nb3, but White has another powerful
idea.} 11. b4 $1 axb3 12. Nxb3 {White ruins his queenside pawn structure, but
as we will see later, this doesn't matter. The open b-file is more important
than the pawn structure.} Ba3 13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Rab1 {Black's biggest problem is
that there will be no safe place for his king.} Na5 15. Nbd4 Qxc3 $4 {This is
too optimistic. Now White gets a big advantage.} 16. Nc2 $1 Nec6 17. Rb5 $1 {
[%cal Rf4d2] Suddenly Black's queen is in big danger.} Nb4 18. Rxb4 Bxb4 19.
Bd2 Qb2 20. Bxb4 $18 {The rest is a simple technique} Nc6 21. Bd6 Rxa2 22. Qd2
h6 23. h4 Ne7 24. Qe3 Nc8 25. Bb4 Ra4 26. Qd2 Bc6 27. Nfd4 Kd7 28. Qf4 Ke8 29.
Nb5 f6 30. exf6 Qxf6 31. Qc7 Bd7 32. h5 Rxb4 33. Nxb4 Qe7 34. Bg6+ Kf8 35. Re1
1-0

