{If you want to improve your understanding of the Advanced Variation, I
recommend you carefully study the games of GM Alexei Shirov. He has many
beautiful wins with White in this line.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6
5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Nh6 {very often Black develops his knight to h6 in order not
to close the f8 bishop} 7. b4 ({the immediate} 7. Bxh6 $6 Qxb2 {is very good
for Black}) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5 9. Bb2 Be7 10. h4 h5 11. Bd3 a5 12. Bxf5 exf5
{We achieve one of the most popular structures in Advanced French. Black
voluntarily ruins his structure, but his position is quite solid. Very soon,
the bishop will come on e6 to cover the weak d5-pawn and in the long run, the
bishop pair could be an important factor. On the other hand, White also has
some benefits. The d5-pawn is eternally weak. and White has some perfect
outposts for his knights, for example, f4. Typical plan for White in this
structure is to try to close the queenside, if it is possible to win some
space there with the pawns on a4-b5 and then transfer his play on the kingside.
} 13. Nc3 Be6 14. b5 Na7 15. a4 {The first part of the plan is already done.}
Nc8 16. O-O Qd8 17. g3 Nb6 18. Ba3 {another important idea is to exchange the
dark-squared bishops. Then Black doesn't have a bishop pair and the dark
squares will be fragile} Rc8 19. Ne2 Nc4 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Nf4 {The third part
of the plan is to transfer the knight to f4.} g6 {this move weakens, even more,
the dark squares.} 22. Ng5 {The rest is a simple technique} Rg8 23. Nh7 Qd8 24.
Nf6+ Kf8 25. Qf3 Nd2 26. Qa3+ Kg7 27. Rfc1 Nc4 28. Qf3 Nd2 29. Qe3 1-0

