1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Nh6 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. cxd4
Nf5 9. Bxf5 exf5 {The position resembles Shirov's game. This time Black is a
strong grandmaster, but the current Russian champion Nikita Vitugov provides
us with a model game on how to handle this position.} 10. Nc3 Be6 11. O-O Be7
12. Na4 Qd8 13. b4 {Remember: first occupy as much space as possible on the
queenside.} O-O 14. Be3 b6 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. Nb2 Rfc8 17. Nd3 Rc7 18. Nf4 Rac8
19. Nh5 {Bg5 is the strategical threat.} Qd8 20. Rfc1 Nb8 21. Rxc7 Rxc7 22. Bg5
{White still manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} Bxg5 23. Nxg5 h6
24. Nf3 Nd7 25. h4 Qc8 26. Ne1 Rc4 27. a4 Qd8 28. g3 Qc7 29. Nf4 a6 30. h5 Nb8
31. b5 a5 32. Neg2 Rc2 33. Qe1 Qd8 34. Ne3 Rc8 35. Rc1 Nd7 36. Rxc8 Qxc8 37.
Nfxd5 1-0

