{The other hero of the Advanced Variation is GM Alexander Grischuk} 1. e4 e6 2.
d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nh6 6. a3 Nf5 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Bb2 O-O
10. Bd3 a6 11. O-O f6 12. Bxf5 {Grischuk decides that after f7-f6 is the right
time to enter the well-known structure. This small pawn move changes the
situation, the e-file will be open at some point and the bishop on e6 loses
his stability.} exf5 13. Nc3 f4 {Otherwise, this square will be occupied by
White's knight} 14. Re1 Kh8 15. Qb3 Be6 16. Re2 $2 (16. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Re2c1,
Rc1d3]}) 16... f5 (16... fxe5 $1 {Black misses his chances to gain a big
advantage.} 17. dxe5 (17. Nxe5 Nxd4) 17... d4 18. Qxe6 dxc3 19. Bxc3 Qd3 $19)
17. Rc2 Rc8 18. Na4 b6 $2 {This move is a big mistake, Black prevents the
knight from coming to c5, but now the queenside loses his stability} 19. Rac1
Nb8 20. Rxc8 Bxc8 21. b5 $1 $18 {a great move that fixes the weakness on b6} a5
22. Nc3 Be6 23. a4 g5 {Black desperately tries counterplay on the kingside.}
24. Ba3 {but Grischuk follows the strategical ideas in this structure: to
exchange the dark-squared bishop} Rg8 25. Ne2 h6 26. Rc3 Qf8 27. h4 Rg7 28.
hxg5 hxg5 29. Nxg5 $1 {Nice tactical finish} Rxg5 30. Nxf4 Bg8 31. Rc7 {
[%cal Rb3h3] Despite his mistake on the move 16, Grischuk played a fantastic
game.} 1-0

