{[%evp 0,45,23,39,30,33,33,6,13,-5,-5,-5,-2,-12,-12,-35,-28,-59,-53,-47,-42,
-42,-47,-43,-33,-101,-94,-124,-97,-120,-104,-132,-104,-185,-71,21,133,191,179,
-64,193,255,573,690,686,686,699,699]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5.
Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O Bd7 {[%csl Gd4]} 8. Re1 {This is the starting
position of the modern tabya in Advanced French. White is sacrificing a pawn
for quick development. Black's main problem is that finding a safe place for
his king and developing the kingside would be tough. Both Black's minor pieces
on the kingside have only one good square (e7). On the other hand, White has
several ways to develop his initiative, depending on Black's reply. White has
three plans to develop the initiative: 1.a3 followed by b4, trying to force
Black to take on c3 with a knight still on b1. 2.Nd2-b3 forcing Black to take.
Then after dxc3 bxc3, White has the semi-open b-file at his disposal and also
the advanced c3-c4. 3. Playing c4 trying to exchange the d5-pawn and get the
squares "c4" and "e4" at our control.} (8. Nbd2 {Magnus tried this move, which
also looks logical, but I think it limits White's options. Although it is
perfectly playable and leads to interesting positions} Rc8 (8... dxc3 {looks
principal} 9. bxc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga1b1,Gc3c4]} Nge7 ({If} 9... f6 {then
White has a strong reply at his disposal} 10. c4 $1 fxe5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Re1
Bd6 (12... e4 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Rxe4+ Be7 16. Bf4 Qc8 17. Qb3 $44 {
[%cal Gf3g5]}) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3) 10. Re1 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gc3c4] White has
some initiative on the b-file and also the advance c3-c4 is coming}) (8... Nge7
9. Nb3 dxc3 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. Re1) 9. Nb3 dxc3 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. Re1 Nge7 12. h4
$1 Ng6 13. Qe2 Be7 14. h5 Ngxe5 $2 (14... Nh4 $1 15. Nxh4 Bxh4 16. h6 g6 17.
Ba3 {White is still slightly better, but the fight just started}) 15. Nxe5 Qxe5
16. Qxe5 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 Bf6 18. Re3 Rxc3 19. Rb1 d4 20. Rg3 O-O 21. Bb2 {
Magnus easily converts his extra material 1-0 (47) Carlsen,M (2863)
-Harikrishna,P (2732) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 8... Rc8 (8... Nh6 {when an
opening specialist as Bluebaum is playing this move, it deserves very serious
attention.} 9. c4 $1 dxc4 10. Bxc4 {[%cal Rb1d2,Rd2e4]} Nf5 (10... Be7 11. Nbd2
Nf5 12. Ne4 O-O 13. a3 Rac8 14. Bd3 {[%cal Rb2b4] despite his extra pawn, it
is hard to suggest a good idea for Black in this position} h6 15. b4 a6 16. Bf4
Bd8 17. Nc5 $16 {½- (107) ½ (107) Jones,G (2670)-Bluebaum,M (2670) Chess.com
INT 2020}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gc6b4,Rb1d2,Rc4d3,Rd2e4,Rd2c4]}) (8... a6 {This move
was played by the "french" specialist GM Meier and it deserves attention.
Black is not in a hurry to play Ne7 or Rc8 and is waiting for White's reply.
He takes the b5-square under control and frees the a7-square for his pieces.}
9. Nbd2 (9. h4 {we can see Black's idea in the following line} dxc3 10. Nxc3
Bc5 11. Qe2 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 $17 {[%cal Gc3b5] and White can't play Nb5: 0-1 
(28) Barrenechea Bahamonde,G (2208)-Arribas Lopez,A (2546) Porto 2015}) 9...
dxc3 (9... Nge7 10. Nb3 (10. h4 {The primary h4 is also possible and could
transpose to the main line}) 10... dxc3 11. bxc3 Ng6 12. h4 Qc7 13. Qe2 f6 14.
exf6 gxf6 15. c4 O-O-O 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Bxg6 (17. Be3 Nge5 $4 18. Nxe5 fxe5
19. Rec1 d4 20. Bd2 Ba3 21. Ba5 Qd6 22. Bxa6 Kb8 23. Bxb7 Bxc1 (23... d3 $1
$132) 24. Qa6 Na7 25. Qxd6+ {1-0 (25) Kiolbasa,O (2399)-Zatonskih,A (2403)
Warsaw 2021}) 17... hxg6 18. Bb2 {[%cal Rb3d4,Ra1c1] Black still has few
problems to solve in the game ½- (33) ½ (33) Kiolbasa,O (2399)-Osmak,I (2419)
Wroclaw 2021}) 10. bxc3 Bc5 11. Qe2 Na5 {[%cal Gd7b5]} (11... Nge7 12. Rb1 Qa7
13. Nb3 Bb6 14. a4 $14 {[%cal Rc1a3]}) 12. Rb1 (12. c4 {was never tried in
practice, but seems good too} dxc4 13. Bxc4 $1 Bc6 14. Ng5 Nxc4 $2 (14... Rd8
15. Rb1 Bxf2+ $1 16. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Rxd2+ 18. Bxd2 Nxc4 19. Bb4 {The
engine said that Black is completely ok here, but I would prefer to play with
the exchange}) 15. Nxc4 Qc7 16. Be3 $16 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 $18 {[%cal Rc4d6]}) 12...
Qc7 13. c4 dxc4 14. Nxc4 (14. Bc2 {Berg implied an original idea, but Black
seems to be better after} Bc6 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Ne7 17. Bd2 Nec6 $15 {
[%cal Re8c8] 0-1 (65) Berg,E (2543)-Meier,G (2641) Vaxjo 2015}) 14... Nxc4 15.
Bxc4 Ne7 16. Ng5 $44 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge2g4,Rg5e4] with a decent compensation
for the sacrificing pawn}) (8... dxc3 {Taking the pawn immediately seems risky}
9. Nxc3 Nge7 10. h4 {The rule in these positions is that when Black's knight
comes to e7, we are playing h4 and ready to meet Ng6 with h5.} a6 11. Be3 $1 {
It is essential to know that this move is possible and we are not losing a
piece after d5-d4} (11. h5) 11... d4 (11... Qd8 12. Na4 Nf5 13. Bxf5 (13. Bb6
$1 Qc8 (13... Qe7 14. Bxf5 exf5 15. e6 $18 {[%cal Rf3g5]}) 14. Rc1 $14) 13...
exf5 14. Nb6 $14 {1-0 (33) Atakhan,A (2357)-Seletsky,G (2298) Chess.com INT
2021}) 12. Nxd4 $1 Nxd4 13. Be4 {White is taking the piece back} Nec6 14. Bxc6
Bxc6 15. Bxd4 Bc5 (15... Qc7 16. Qg4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Ra1c1]}) 16. Na4
$18) 9. Nbd2 dxc3 (9... Nge7 10. Nb3 dxc3 11. bxc3 Na5 $1 {Black is trying to
get counterplay on the queenside and to free the c6-square for his other
knight.} 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Nxa5 Qxa5 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Ga5][%cal
Ga2a4]} Nf5 $2 {this move is a big mistake. White gets a big advantage after:}
(15... Nc6 16. a4 {[%cal Rd3b5]} Qxa4 17. Ra1 Qg4 18. h3 Qh5 19. Qf1 $14 {
[%cal Rg2g4]}) (15... Ng6 16. a4 Bxa4 17. Ra1 b5 18. h4 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal
Rh4h5]}) 16. Bxf5 exf5 17. e6 $1 Bxe6 18. Nd4 Be7 19. Bg5 $1 Qc5 20. Nxe6 fxe6
21. Qxe6 Rc7 22. Rbd1 {1-0 (27) Kryvoruchko,Y (2689)-Christiansen,J (2609)
Struga 2021}) 10. bxc3 Na5 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. c4 $1 dxc4 13. Bc2 $1 {remember
this idea} Ne7 (13... Bc6 {It is necessary to exchange the knight on e4} 14.
Ne4 Rd8 15. Qe2 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 {White has decent compensation for the two pawns,
but the game is still on.}) 14. Ng5 h6 15. Nde4 Nd5 16. Qh5 g6 17. Nd6+ $1 Bxd6
18. Bxg6 Bxe5 19. Nxf7 Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Nf6 21. Nxh8+ Ke7 22. Qxh6 Rg8 23. Bg5 {
1-0 (23) Gavrilescu,D (2511)-Laptii,N (2180) Bucharest 2022} *

