{[%evp 0,25,35,34,34,33,33,18,18,-6,-6,-6,-14,-14,-24,-29,-37,-76,-66,-60,-34,
-60,-45,-45,-51,-72,-72,-72]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O Bd7 {[%csl Gd4]} 8. Re1 {This is the starting position of
the modern tabya in Advanced French. White is sacrificing a pawn for quick
development. Black's main problem is that finding a safe place for his king
and developing the kingside would be tough. Both Black's minor pieces on the
kingside have only one good square (e7). On the other hand, White has several
ways to develop his initiative, depending on Black's reply.  White has three
plans to develop the initiative: 1.a3 followed by b4, trying to force Black to
take on c3 with a knight still on b1. 2.Nd2-b3 forcing Black to take. Then
after dxc3 bxc3, White has the semi-open b-file at his disposal and also the
advanced c3-c4. 3. We are playing c4, trying to exchange the d5-pawn and get
the squares "c4" and "e4" under our control.} Nge7 {[%csl Gc8]} 9. h4 h6 {
is a popular line. Black is stopping Ng5 and preparing g5 at an appropriate
moment.} (9... a6 $5 10. a3 $5 (10. Nbd2 {this move transposes to 8...a6 and
probably is the best choice}) 10... dxc3 11. Nxc3 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gb3]} 12. Nxd4
Qxd4 13. g3 {[%cal Rc1e3] with a compensation for the pawn.}) (9... Nf5 10.
Bxf5 exf5 11. cxd4 {You can find a few model games on how to handle this
structure in the database. In this particular position, White tried different
ideas.} Be6 12. Nc3 h6 13. Ne2 (13. a3 Be7 14. b4 Rc8 15. Na4 (15. Ne2 {
[%cal Rd1d3,Rc1d2,Re2f4] looks promising too}) 15... Qb5 16. Bd2 b6 17. Rc1 O-O
18. Nc3 Qd3 19. Re3 Qc4 20. Be1 Nb8 21. h5 f4 22. Ne2 fxe3 23. Rxc4 exf2+ 24.
Bxf2 Rxc4 25. Nf4 {White manages to win this wild game 1-0 (39) Jones,G (2670)
-Iskusnyh,S (2473) Chess.com INT 2020}) (13. h5 Be7 14. Re3 a6 15. a3 Rc8 16.
Na4 Qa7 17. Rc3 O-O 18. Nc5 $2 {this is too premature} Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Qb8 (19...
Nxd4 $1 $19) 20. Bf4 Rc7 21. Rac1 $14 {1-0 (59) Shevchenko,K (2599)-Sonis,F 
(2477) Europe Echecs INT 2021}) 13... Be7 14. h5 O-O 15. Nf4 (15. Rb1 Rfc8 16.
Nf4 a5 17. Kh1 Nb4 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Rg1 $13 {1-0 (74) Piorun,K (2640)
-Vastrukhin,O (2376) Warsaw 2021}) 15... Rfc8 (15... Rac8 16. Re3 $14 {[%cal
Re3b3,Re3c3]}) 16. Re3 a5 (16... Na5 17. b3 Rc7 18. Rd3 $14) 17. Rb3 Qa7 18. a4
$14 (18. Be3)) (9... h5 {is stopping the advance h4-h5, but weakens the
kingside too much.} 10. Nbd2 dxc3 11. bxc3 Nf5 12. Rb1 (12. Nb3 Be7 13. Bxf5
exf5 14. Qxd5 (14. Rb1 $1 $14) 14... Be6 15. Qd1 O-O 16. Nfd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4
Rad8 18. Be3 f4 19. Bxf4 {½-½  (19) Arraga,G (1951)-Salcedo,C (1722) Buenos
Aires 2011}) 12... Qc7 13. c4 $1 $16) (9... Nc8 $6 {Anatoly Karpov introduced
this maneuver in a similar structure in Caro Can, but it doesn't work well
here.} 10. Ng5 $1 h6 (10... Be7 11. Qh5 g6 12. Qg4 dxc3 13. Nxc3 $16) 11. Qh5
Nd8 12. Nxf7 Nxf7 13. Bg6 $16) 10. h5 a6 (10... Qc7 {[%csl Gd4]} 11. Nxd4 $14 {
White could simply takes the pawn back with a slightly better position.} (11.
Qe2 {continue playing in a gambit style is also possible} Nc8 12. a3 {[%csl
Gd4][%cal Gc3d4]} (12. cxd4 Nb4) 12... dxc3 13. Nxc3 $44)) (10... Rc8 11. Na3 {
[%cal Rc3c4]} (11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2b3]} dxc3 12. bxc3 Na5 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. Nb3
Nxb3 15. axb3 Nc6 16. Bf4 Be7 17. b4 {1-0 (44) Shevchenko,K (2652)-Rustemov,A 
(2525) Chess.com INT 2022}) 11... dxc3 12. bxc3 a6 (12... Na5 13. Rb1 $16) 13.
Rb1 Qc7 14. c4) (10... g5 $5 11. hxg6 (11. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb5d6]}) (11. Nh2
O-O-O 12. Ng4 Bg7 {the bishop is not doing much on g7} (12... Nf5 $1) 13. a4 a6
14. Na3 dxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7 16. Qe2 $18 {1-0 (36) Frank Nielsen,M (2002)-Furrer,
C (2082) Copenhagen 2014}) 11... Nxg6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. a4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ra4a5,
Rb1a3,Rd1d3]}) 11. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2]} Rd8 12. b4 Nc8 13. Nxd4 {1-0 (46)
Ponkratov,P (2641) -Mirzoev,A (2476) Guwahati 2022} *

