{[%evp 0,56,34,19,41,44,27,13,13,-3,-5,7,11,1,8,3,19,-1,38,-13,-3,31,4,0,3,0,0,
3,12,7,12,12,9,11,3,18,18,0,31,42,23,23,91,72,85,70,68,54,122,71,97,118,83,93,
94,63,407,435,916]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 {
The drawback of the move 5...Bd7 is that it doesn't put any pressure on d4 and
White can finish the development easily.} (6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O dxc3 8. Nxc3 {
with a queen on d8, this gambit is suspicious. White still has a compensation,
but I am not sure if it is enough.}) 6... Rc8 {Nowadays this is a popular
system. Black first activate his queenside and then decides what to do with
the kingside.} 7. O-O {C02: French: Advance Variation.} h6 (7... a6 8. Na3 {
Shirov chooses this move and create a nice miniature} (8. a3 c4 9. Nbd2 Na5 10.
Ne1 Ne7 11. g4 {This is also possible and the engines claims that White is
slightly better. It is possible that this is true, but this close position is
not everyone's cup of tea. 1-0 (55) Maghsoodloo,P (2676)-Volkov,S (2557)
Lichess.org INT 2020}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nge7 10. Nc2 Nf5 11. g4 Nfe7 12. Ng5
h6 13. Nh3 h5 14. gxh5 Nf5 15. Bg4 Qh4 16. Bg5 {1-0 (16) Shirov,A (2662)-Meier,
G (2628) Tornelo INT 2020}) 8. Be3 {[#]} Qb6 $146 9. dxc5 {White has an edge.}
Bxc5 (9... Qxb2 {with more complications.} 10. Nbd2 Qxc3 11. Rb1 Nge7) 10. Bxc5
Qxc5 11. Nbd2 Nge7 12. Nb3 {Anand enters the well known structure with a pawn
on e5 and a free square on d4.} Qb6 13. Bd3 Na5 14. Nxa5 Qxa5 15. a4 {[%cal
Ba2a4,Ba4a5][%mdl 32]} O-O 16. Re1 Qb6 17. Qd2 a6 18. h4 Rc7 19. a5 Qc5 20. Re3
Nf5 21. Bxf5 {Transforming to a structure which we already know. But now with
only one minor pieces on the board, White is clearly better. Behind the knight
on d4 and the pawn on e5, White can organize a deadly attack.} exf5 22. Nd4 Qe7
23. g3 {[%cal Bg2g3,Bg3f4][%mdl 32]} h5 (23... Rc5 $142) 24. Qe2 g6 {[%cal
Of5f4]} 25. e6 f4 26. gxf4 {White is more active.} fxe6 27. Rg3 Qxh4 $2 {
[%mdl 8192] [#]} (27... Qg7 $16) 28. Qe5 $18 Rc4 1-0

