{[%evp 0,68,19,29,65,74,59,59,76,76,47,47,40,40,74,55,71,9,15,-42,0,-10,3,-10,
-10,-11,8,-1,13,18,13,-11,0,-5,7,-15,-12,-16,-14,-32,-30,-15,-16,-66,-26,-92,
-86,-120,-86,-100,-73,-100,-85,-94,-135,-220,-227,-233,-233,-217,-256,-226,
-246,-280,-278,-279,-264,-400,-428,-421,-454]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4.
Bd3 Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 6. Ne2 {This move is quite similar to 6.Nf3 which is my
preferred square for the knight.} Qb6 7. O-O c5 {Most inexperienced players
will automatically place c2-c3 without thinking. In fact, after ...c6-c5,White
has three playable possibilities: 1) c2-c3 (not the most frequent one) 2) dxc5
3) c2-c4  When possible, you should try to go for the third option. With the
advance c2-c4, White is trying to make use of his space advantage and
g5-bishop (which is not the case here), thus getting great attacking
possibilities.} 8. c3 Nc6 9. f4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nh6 11. Nd2 Nf5 12. Nf3 h5 13.
Bd2 a5 {This is a very deep positional move, preventing all kind of b2-b4
ideas. Additionally, this move contains a hidden positional trap. White fails
for it by playing} 14. a3 Qa6 {So that was Capablanca's idea. He played a5,
supposedly to control the b4-square. Actually his idea was to exchange the
queens and force the transition into a favourable endgame.} 15. Qxa6 Rxa6 {
Black is doing really great in such positions. We dismiss them once and for
all. I never want to see such a.game again in my life! Afterwards, Capablanca
coverted his advantage in a flawless way.} 16. Rac1 Kd7 17. Rc2 Be7 18. Rfc1
Bd8 19. Kf2 Bb6 20. Be3 a4 21. Rd1 Rc8 22. Nc3 Na5 23. Ke2 Nc4 24. Bc1 Bd8 25.
Kd3 Rb8 26. Rg1 b5 27. g4 hxg4 28. Rxg4 b4 29. axb4 Rxb4 30. Nd1 Rc6 31. h4 g6
32. Bd2 Nxd2 33. Rxd2 Rb3+ 34. Ke2 Ba5 0-1

