{[%evp 0,84,17,13,70,71,59,74,47,45,56,56,58,54,78,62,61,67,60,59,62,31,9,15,
16,19,7,6,0,-10,-7,-10,34,21,10,0,1,-13,32,-10,72,-3,-8,-33,-34,-44,-44,-60,
-37,-52,-42,-74,-43,-82,-60,-65,-63,-78,-68,-96,-79,-79,-78,-78,-103,-126,-117,
-128,-107,-107,-119,-123,-163,-154,-175,-195,-206,-296,-319,-381,-384,-415,
-416,-553,-591,-560,-603] Now, let's take a look at a similar game of mine
played a long time ago.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6.
Qxd3 {We will see this famous check on many occasions. In this concrete case,
Black's idea is to exchange the queens via a6.} Qa5+ 7. c3 Qa6 8. Qxa6 Nxa6 {
Black is already better in this position. After the exchange of the queens,
White's space advantage is irrelevant.} 9. Nbd2 Ne7 10. Nf1 ({Nothing changes} 
10. Nb3 h5 11. Bf4 Nf5 12. Ke2 (12. Na5 Rb8) 12... Be7 {It's important to
point out that in such structures, the attempt to expand on the kingside by
means of} 13. h3 {is well met by} h4 {Having stopped White's kingside play,
Black is ready to expand on the other wing.}) 10... c5 11. Bd2 Nc6 12. Ne3 Rc8
{The most natural continuation. Black is ready to open the c-file.} ({In such
positions, starting with} 12... Kd7 {is possible as well. Note that the jump}
13. Ng5 {should be answered with} f6 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Nf3 Bd6 {Black is
already significantly better.}) 13. Ke2 Be7 14. Rhc1 cxd4 (14... c4 15. b3 b5
16. a4) 15. cxd4 Kd7 {Of course, the king belongs to the centre.} (15... O-O $2
) 16. a3 Nc7 17. Nc2 f6 {This is another typical break in French type of
structures. Black wants to either take on e5 (provoking weakness and creating
protected passer) or force exf6. In the later case, he will build a strong
centre by recapturing with the g-pawn.} 18. b4 ({Obviously, after} 18. exf6
gxf6 19. Be3 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black is better. He is ready to follow with ...
e6-e5.}) 18... b5 {[%cal Gc7a8,Ga8b6,Gb6c4] A strong positional idea. I am
preparing the maneuver ...Nc7-a8-b6-c4.} 19. Nce1 (19. a4 bxa4 20. Rxa4 Nb5 $17
) 19... Na8 20. Nd3 Nb6 21. Nc5+ Bxc5 22. bxc5 Nc4 {Black has a huge advantage.
Later on, I managed to convert it into a full point.} 23. exf6 gxf6 24. Rcb1
Rb8 25. Bf4 e5 26. Be3 h6 27. Rd1 Ke6 $1 28. Ra2 (28. dxe5 fxe5 29. g3 d4 30.
Bc1 Kd5 $19) 28... a5 29. Kf1 Ra8 30. Nd2 exd4 31. Nxc4 dxc4 32. Bxd4 Rhd8 33.
Re1+ Kf7 34. Be3 b4 (34... h5 35. Rc1 a4 $19) 35. axb4 axb4 36. Rc2 c3 37. Rb1
Ke6 $3 38. Ke2 (38. Bxh6 Nd4 $19 (38... Kd5 39. Bf4 Kc4 $19)) 38... Kd5 39. f4
(39. Kd3 Ne5+ 40. Ke2 Kc4 41. f4 Nc6) 39... Kc4 40. Rbc1 Rd3 (40... Re8 41. Kf3
Rad8 42. Re2 (42. Bf2 f5 43. g3 Rd3+ 44. Kg2 b3) 42... b3 $19) 41. Bf2 Re8+ 42.
Kf1 b3 0-1

