{Even though this game does not feature the Caro-Kann, it's very relevant for
our variation. You will see that White's space advantage promises him
excellent chances in an eventual knight endgame.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6
4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nce2 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. f4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Qa5 10. a3 Bxd2+
11. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Na5 13. Nc1 Nc4+ 14. Kc3 Ne3 15. Nd3 Nxf1 16. Rxf1 b6
17. Nf3 Ba6 18. Rc1 Bxd3 19. Kxd3 Ke7 20. Rc7 Rhc8 21. Rhc1 Rxc7 22. Rxc7 Kd8
23. Rc6 h6 24. g4 Rc8 25. Rxc8+ Kxc8 {This is the starting position of our
survey. Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, White can create a lot of
practical problems for his opponent. The first step is to gain as much space
as possible.} 26. h4 Kd8 27. h5 $1 {A typical way of fixing the structure.
White has 2 winning plans: 1) put pressure on the h6-pawn by playing g4-g5
followed by Nh2-g4 2) break with f4-f5-f6 (after the eventual ...gxf6 exf6,
White will be threatening g4-g5)} Ke7 ({It's very important that after} 27...
f6 28. Ke3 fxe5 {the right way to recapture is} 29. dxe5 $3 $18 {The d5-passed
pawn is meaningless while Black cannot fight against White's kingside pawn
mass.}) ({In case of} 27... Nb8 {White can go for} 28. f5 Nc6 29. f6 gxf6 30.
exf6 {[%cal Gg4g5] We have already mentioned this typical idea. Black is
helpless in view of the break g4-g5.}) 28. g5 $3 {[%cal Gf3h2,Gh2g4] When
f4-f5-f6 does not work, we go for this idea. White is planning Nh2-g4. Note
that before playing the advance g4-g5, you should always calculate the
counterbreak ...g7-g6. Sometimes, this option allows Black to create a passed
pawn on the h-file.} hxg5 {This move allows White to create a distant passed
pawn.} ({Another option would have been} 28... Nb8 29. Nh2 $3 Kf8 30. gxh6 $1 {
This is the right approach.} ({After} 30. Ng4 {Black has the thematic} g6 $1 ({
Obviously, after} 30... hxg5 31. fxg5 Nc6 32. Kc3 $16 {White is nearly winning.
})) 30... gxh6 31. Ng4 Kg7 32. f5 $3 {Another typical break!} Nc6 (32... exf5
33. Ne3) 33. f6+ (33. Ne3) 33... Kh7 34. Kc3 {Since Black is playing without a
king, White can start playing on the queenside.} b5 35. Nf2 a5 36. Nd3 Kg8 37.
Nc5 Kf8 38. Nb7 Kg8 39. Nd6 b4+ 40. Kd3 {[%cal Gd3c2,Gc2b3,Gb3a4,Gd6b5] White
has a clear winning plan - Nb5 followed by Kc2-b3-a4. The following line is
quite illustrative.} Kf8 41. Nb5 Ke8 42. Kc2 Kd7 43. Kb3 Ke8 44. Ka4 bxa3 45.
bxa3 Kd7 46. Nd6 Nxd4 47. Nxf7 $18) 29. fxg5 f6 30. h6 ({Another winning line
would have been} 30. exf6+ gxf6 31. g6 Kf8 32. h6 e5 33. Nh4 $18) 30... gxh6
31. gxf6+ Nxf6 32. exf6+ Kxf6 33. Ke3 Kf5 34. Ne5 h5 35. Nf3 Kg4 36. Ne5+ Kg3
37. Ng6 Kg4 38. b4 b5 39. Kf2 Kf5 40. Ne5 Ke4 41. Nc6 a6 42. Kg3 1-0

