{[%evp 0,95,27,22,51,50,103,51,51,38,49,45,31,20,13,16,41,50,42,51,52,52,44,31,
38,25,25,28,28,12,36,10,38,30,30,30,30,30,30,20,74,13,12,11,11,11,11,-14,8,4,
10,5,5,3,5,5,2,6,9,3,12,0,22,25,17,17,24,24,26,17,74,73,85,85,64,64,84,80,87,
71,66,88,88,85,85,85,85,85,85,85,134,162,176,172,516,600,672,704]} {Let's take
a look at another instructive knight endgame. The first important position
arises after 28.Kc3.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O Nc6
6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1 g6 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Be3 Rfd8 12. Rc1 d5
13. e5 Ne4 14. Qb3 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Na5 16. Qc2 Rac8 17. Rc1 Rxc3 18. Qxc3 Nc4 19.
b3 Nb6 20. Qc7 Rc8 21. Qxd7 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 Nxd7 23. Ba3 Bf8 24. Kf1 e6 25. Bxf8
Kxf8 26. Ke2 Ke7 27. Kd3 Nb8 28. Kc3 {This position is not a such a simple
draw as it might look at the first sight. Black should already reckon with the
threat of Ng5. Therefore, he has played} h6 ({In case of} 28... Nc6 {White has
the following spectacular maneuver -} 29. Ng5 h6 30. Nh7 {[%csl Rh6][%cal
Gh7f6,Gf6g8,Gf6g4,Gg4h6,Gg8h6,Gh6h5] White wants to provoke the advance ...
h6-h5 by means of the maneuver Nf6-g4 (g8). Once Black plays ...h6-h5, White
will immediately fix the pawn with h2-h4. After fixing the pawn, he will break
with f2-f3 followed by g2-g4.} a6 31. Nf6 ({It's also possible to start with} 
31. h4) 31... Kd8 32. Ng4 h5 33. Nf6 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf2f3,Gg2g4] It's already
clear that after h2-h4, White wants to create a distant passed pawn by means
of f2-f3 followed by g2-g4. Of course, after} Ne7 34. h4 Nf5 35. g3 {Things
are not that simple. Nevertheless, Black should handle this position with care.
}) ({Let's suppose that Black starts with} 28... h5 {In this case, White will
immediately fix the pawn by means of} 29. h4 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gf2f3,Gg2g4]
preparing the break g2-g4. A possible line would be} Nc6 30. Ng5 b6 31. f3 Nd8
32. g4 {Black is already in danger.} hxg4 ({After} 32... Nc6 33. Nh3 b5 34. Nf4
{Black is forced to take on g4. Once again, you should take into consideration
the break ...g6-g5. Fortunately, it does not work here.}) 33. fxg4 Kf8 34. Nf3
{While the black king is tied to White's kingside passer, we are going to win
on the other side of the board.}) 29. h4 Kd7 30. Nh2 Nc6 31. Ng4 h5 32. Nf6+
Kd8 33. f3 b5 34. g4 hxg4 35. fxg4 {This is a perfect execution of the entire
strategy. White has converted his advantage in a flawless way.} b4+ 36. Kd3 Ke7
37. h5 gxh5 38. gxh5 Kf8 39. h6 Ne7 40. Nh7+ Kg8 41. Ng5 Ng6 42. Ke3 Kf8 43.
Kf3 Ke7 44. Kg4 Nh8 45. Kh5 f6 46. Nf3 f5 47. h7 Kf8 48. Kh6 1-0

