{[%evp 0,65,19,31,84,52,52,52,52,19,48,-4,12,10,50,47,34,44,38,30,35,40,34,24,
29,16,27,34,58,58,54,32,30,29,52,56,45,63,68,34,71,57,66,38,44,32,49,52,84,82,
80,68,80,79,72,62,62,60,72,42,309,318,318,312,309,309,793,880]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4
d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. c4 {Even though my main suggestion would be 5.Bd3,
this move does not change the character of the game. Sooner or later White
will exchange on d5. When Black recaptures with the c-pawn, we get the same
structure as when Black plays ...c6-c5 followed by ...cxd4.} e6 6. Nc3 Be7 7.
cxd5 cxd5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nc6 10. Nf3 Nh6 {The first important moment.
Black is planning to proceed with ...Nf5 in this position. When you see the
move ...Nh6, you can either ingore it or play Bxh6. That's what Dubov did in
the game.} 11. Bxh6 {Note that we will give our bishop for the knight only on
the h6-square. The idea is that Black will waste a lot of time in order to
secure the safety of his king and bring the h6-rook back into play. The only
constructive plan for Black in such positions is the maneuver ...Rg6-g4. In
this concrete case, however, the rook maneuver does not work.} Rxh6 12. Rc1 {
White is preparing active actions on the queenside. The maneuver Na4-c5 is the
main positional ideal. Once Black gives his bishop for the knight, White will
immediately establish a knight on g5. In this case, the kingside attack based
on the advance g3-g4 will be very difficult to deal with.} Kf8 13. g3 g6 14.
O-O {Before playing such a move, we obviously need to calculate the advance ...
g6-g5. Probably, Dubov did it.} ({A bit more cautious would have been} 14. Kf1
Kg7 15. Kg2 Rh8 16. Na4 {with the same idea as in the game.}) 14... Kg7 ({
Black should have seriously considered} 14... g5) 15. Na4 Rh8 16. Nc5 {The
c5-knight is very annoying. Therefore, Artemiev played} Bxc5 ({In case of} 
16... Qb6 {White could play} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gc1c3,Gf1c1,Gd2f4] with
possibilities to play on both wings.}) 17. Rxc5 {White will combine his
queenside pressure with a kingside attack. Under favourable circumstances, he
will establish a knight on g5 and will follow with g3-g4.} Qd7 18. Rfc1 Rhc8
19. Qc3 a5 20. a3 a4 21. Ne1 Qe7 22. Nf3 Qd7 23. Kg2 Rc7 24. Qc2 Qd8 25. Qd1
Rd7 26. Ng5 {Finally, White is ready to execute his main plan.} Ra6 27. g4 $1 {
The attack is unstoppable.} Qh8 28. Qf3 Rb6 29. gxh5 Qxh5 30. Qf6+ Kg8 31. Ra5
$1 {Well-calculated final blow!} Qg4+ 32. Kf1 Nd8 33. Ra8 1-0

