{This is another instructive example featuring the strategy based on Bxh6.
Contrary to Artemiev, Karpov employed the right idea - ...Rg6-g4. Even this
defence, however, proved to be insufficient.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4
h5 5. c4 e6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nc6 10. Nf3 Nb4 11. Qe2
Rc8 12. O-O Nc6 ({Obviously, Black cannot take the pawn with} 12... Bxh4 {After
} 13. Nxh4 Qxh4 14. Nb5 $18 {White is already winning.}) 13. g3 Qd7 14. Bd2 Nh6
15. Bxh6 $1 {Once again, this is the best strategy. Gulko is ready to start
playing on the queenside.} Rxh6 16. Rac1 Kf8 {Before bringing the rook to g4,
Karpov wants to cover the h7-square with the king.} ({The immediate} 16... Rg6
{runs into} 17. Qd3 Rg4 18. Qh7 $18 {with a winning advantage for White.}) 17.
Na4 Rc7 ({Too passive is} 17... g6 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Kg7 20. Rfc1 Rhh8 21.
Qd2 {[%cal Gf3g5] followed by Ng5. The character of the play reminds the game
Dubov - Artemiev.}) 18. Rc3 Rg6 19. Rfc1 Rg4 20. Qd3 Kg8 {Black is just in
time to cover the h7-square.} 21. a3 f6 22. Nc5 Bxc5 23. Rxc5 Qf7 24. b4 $14 {
Even though Black's position remains playable, White is still better in view
of his strong queenside play. Gulko managed to convert his advantage.} a6 25.
Qc3 Rd7 26. a4 Ne7 27. Nh2 Rg6 28. Qd3 Nf5 29. Rc8+ Kh7 30. Kh1 Nh6 31. R1c2
Nf5 32. b5 axb5 33. axb5 Qe7 34. R2c5 b6 35. R5c6 Ra7 36. Nf3 Ra3 37. Qd1 Rg4
38. exf6 Qxf6 39. Ng5+ Rxg5 40. hxg5 Qxg5 41. Rxe6 h4 42. Ree8 hxg3 43. Rh8+
Kg6 44. f4 Ne3 45. Rc6+ Kf7 46. fxg5 Nxd1 47. g6+ Ke7 48. Kg2 Ne3+ 49. Kxg3
