1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 {Our bishop
should occupy the g5-square at the first possible moment. In this way, we make
Black's development very difficult.} Be7 ({The move} 7... Ne7 {is a very bad
idea. For Black is already very difficult to complete the development. Let's
take a look at some sample lines.} 8. Nf3 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5a6] Black is planning
to exchange the queens via a6-square.} ({After} 8... Nd7 9. Nbd2 c5 {Besides
the standard c2-c3, White can consider two additional options - 10.c4 and 10.
dxc5. In this concrete case, the most precise appears to be} 10. c4 {We are
always ready to play an open position in this line!} Qb6 ({Obviously after} 
10... cxd4 11. cxd5 {White has a winning advantage.}) 11. O-O cxd4 12. Bxe7
Bxe7 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nb3 {White is strategically winning.}) 9. Nbd2 Qa6 10.
c4 $1 {We always answer ...Qa6 with this move in order to prevent the exchange
of the queens. The black queen will be quite passive on a6.} dxc4 11. Nxc4 Nd5
12. O-O {Take a closer look at this very typical position. It turns out that
there is no suitable square for the dark-squared bishop. The problem is that
whenever Black plays ...Be7, White will exchange the bishops and get access to
the d6-square. In such a case, the black king will be terribly vulnerable.} Nd7
13. Rfd1 Be7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. b3 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gd3f3,Gc4d6] White has a
winning advantage. He can develop his initiative by means of simple moves such
as Ng5, Qf3, and Nd6.} c5 16. Ng5 cxd4 17. Qf3 $18) 8. Nf3 Nh6 9. Bxh6 {
Sutovsky goes for our familiar strategy.} ({Obviously, there is nothing wrong
with} 9. Nc3) ({or} 9. Nbd2 Nf5 10. g3 $1 {By overprotecting the h4-pawn,
White is getting ready to recapture on g5 with a knight.} Nd7 11. O-O c5 12.
Bxe7 Qxe7 13. c4 {It seems that Black's position will soon ruin.}) 9... Rxh6
10. Nbd2 Na6 {The knight does nothing on a6.} ({Once again, the advance} 10...
c5 {does not solve Black's problems. After} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6 13. c4
dxc4 14. Qxc4 Be7 15. Ne4 {White has a winning initiative.}) 11. c3 {There is
nothing wrong with this natural move.} ({In my opinion, however, a bit more
flexible would have been} 11. a3 {[%cal Gc2c4] keeping the option of playing
c2-c4.}) 11... c5 12. a3 {Preventing ...cxd4 followed by ...Nb4.} Rc8 13. b4 {
White starts gaining space on the queenside.} cxd4 14. cxd4 Kf8 15. Ke2 (15. g3
) 15... g6 16. Qb5 {The idea of this move is to provoke some queenside
weaknesses.} ({Another natural follow up would have been} 16. g3 Kg7 17. Rhc1
Rh8 18. Nb3 Nb8 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. Rc1 Qd7 21. Qc3 {The control of the c-file
gives White a huge advantage.}) 16... Rc7 17. Rac1 Nb8 18. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5]
The knight is heading for the important c5-square.} a6 19. Qd3 Kg7 20. Rxc7
Qxc7 21. Rc1 Qd7 22. Nc5 Bxc5 23. bxc5 {White's advantage is out of question.
After establishing a knight on g5, he will combine his play on the b-file with
a kingside attack. Later on, Sutovsky managed to win a nice game.} (23. Rxc5 {
[%cal Gf3g5] is perfectly playable as well.}) 23... Nc6 24. Rb1 Rh8 25. Qd2 Qe7
26. Qf4 Rb8 27. Rb6 Rc8 28. Ng5 Na5 29. g4 Rh8 30. gxh5 Rxh5 31. Rb1 Rh6 32.
Kf1 Rh8 33. Kg2 Rh5 34. Kg3 Rh8 35. Rb6 Rh5 36. Rd6 Nc6 37. Qf6+ Qxf6 38. exf6+
Kxf6 39. Rd7 Ne7 40. Kg4 Rh8 41. Rxb7 Re8 42. Ra7 a5 43. a4 Kg7 44. Kf4 Kf6 45.
Nh7+ Kg7 46. Ng5 Kf6 47. Rd7 Kg7 48. Ke5 f6+ 49. Kxe6 fxg5 50. Rxe7+ Rxe7+ 51.
Kxe7 gxh4 52. c6 h3 53. c7 h2 54. c8=Q h1=Q 55. Qf8+ Kh7 56. Qf7+ Kh6 57. Qf4+
Kh5 58. Kf6 Qg2 59. Qg3 1-0

