1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 ({On the highest
level, more popular is} 6... Qa5+ {The idea is that after} 7. Nd2 {White
should waste some time in order to put his bishop on g5.}) 7. Bg5 Be7 ({
An important alternative is} 7... Qa5+ 8. Nd2 Nd7 {Putting the knight on d7 is
always a concession. When the knight is on d7, White can always answer ...
c6-c5 with c2-c3.} ({Another possible line would be} 8... Ne7 9. Ngf3 Nf5 10.
O-O Nd7 11. Rfe1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] This typical move introduces a
very important strategic idea. White wants to eliminate the f5-knight by means
of the maneuver Nf1-e3.} ({Another decent option would be} 11. c4 {In this
case, a possible follow up would be} Qa6 12. Qc3 {A typical move. White is
unpinning the queen.} Be7 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. b3 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White is
ready to gain space by means of a2-a4-a5.} ({I am not a big fan of closing the
position with} 14. c5 {even though White keeps some advantage.}) 14... O-O 15.
a4 {As often happens in all these lines, White can play on both wings.}) ({
Another perfectly playable option is} 11. Rfd1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3]}
c5 12. c3 {This move works very well when Black has already committed to ...
Nd7.} ({It goes without saying that we should always calculate} 12. c4 {
since White is always ready to play an open position.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Be7
14. Bxe7 Kxe7 {Despite the simplifications, Black experiences serious problems
due to the vulnerable position of his king. We can now see that the inclusion
of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is highly favourable for White. Black should
constantly reckon with the weakness of the g5-square. White's next step is to
eliminate the f5-knight by means of the maneuver Nd2-f1-e3.} 15. Nf1 Rhc8 16.
Ne3 Nxe3 ({After} 16... g6 17. Nxf5+ gxf5 18. Qe3 {[%csl Rh5] Black's position
is terrible due to his spoiled structure and vulnerable king.}) 17. Qxe3 {
[%cal Ge3g5] White has a dangerous attack. Had the black pawn been on h6, his
position would have been perfectly defendable.})) 9. Ngf3 c5 10. c3 Ne7 11. O-O
Nc6 {At this point, besides the standard moves 12.c4 and 12.a3, White can go
for the following sequence -} 12. Nb3 Qb6 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. b4
Be7 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Nd4 {Black is completely busted. White can already
organize his kingside attack.}) 8. Nf3 Nd7 ({After} 8... Nh6 {Besides the
strategy based on Bxh6, White can play 9.Nbd2 or 9.Nc3. I would like to expain
some interesting ideas related to the later option.} 9. Nc3 Nf5 10. g3 Nd7 ({
Obviously, after} 10... c5 11. dxc5 {White is well prepared to play an open
position.}) 11. Ne2 ({Another possibility would have been} 11. O-O {when after}
c5 $2 {White has} 12. Nxd5 $1 {One of the points behind putting the knight on
c3.}) 11... c5 12. c3 cxd4 13. Nexd4 $1 {The main idea behind the maneuver
Nc3-e2. By taking with the knight, we complete one of the major positional
goals in this line - elimination the f5-knight. Let's take a look at how the
game might develop.} Nxd4 14. cxd4 Qa5+ 15. Kf1 ({There is nothing wrong with} 
15. Ke2) 15... Bxg5 16. Nxg5 $16 {We have already seen this kind of position.
White is almost winning by combining threats on both wings.}) 9. Nbd2 Nh6 ({
Nothing changes after} 9... c5 10. c3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nh6 12. O-O ({Obviously,
the Bxh6 strategy works quite well here. For example, after} 12. Bxh6 Rxh6 13.
g3 g6 14. Kf1 Kf8 15. Kg2 Kg7 16. Rac1 {White has an almost winning position.
The next step is to establish a knight on c5 by means of simple moves such as
a2-a3, b2-b4, and Nb3-c5. After eliminating the e7-bishop, we will put a
knight on g5. Then, White is winning by combining threats on both wings.})
12... Nf5 13. g3 {Protecting the h4-pawn. It's essential to be able to answer .
..Bxg5 with Nxg5.} Qb6 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Rac1 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Nc6 16. Nb3 O-O
17. Ng5 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) 10. c4 {This thematic move is never
a mistake.} ({Probably, I would have preferred} 10. Bxh6 $1 Rxh6 11. g3 c5 12.
c3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb8 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nb3 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gb3c5] We know that our
first priority in this structure is to bring a knight to c5.} Kf8 16. a3 g6 17.
Rfc1 Kg7 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Rh8 20. Rac1 Rc8 21. Ng5 $18 {Black is helpless
against White's threats on both wings. A possible finish would be} Qd7 22. Qf3
{[%cal Gf3f6]} Qe7 23. Qf4 a6 24. b4 Rhf8 25. a4 $18 {[%cal Gb4b5] White is
winning since there is no satisfactory defence against b4-b5.}) 10... Nf5 11.
Rc1 Qb6 12. b3 a5 13. g3 Qa6 14. Kf1 ({Another possibility would have been} 14.
Bxe7 Kxe7 15. O-O Rhd8 16. Ng5 g6 17. Rfd1 Kf8 18. Qc3 (18. Nf1) 18... Kg8 19.
Nf1 Nf8 20. Ne3 $16 {with a huge advantage.}) 14... Ba3 15. Rc2 Nf8 16. Kg2 Ng6
17. Rd1 O-O 18. Nf1 Be7 19. Ne3 Nxe3+ 20. Qxe3 {White has a big advantage. He
managed to efortlessly convert it into a full point.} Bb4 21. Qe2 Rfe8 22. Nh2
dxc4 23. bxc4 c5 24. d5 exd5 25. Rxd5 f6 26. Qxh5 fxg5 27. Rd6 b6 28. Qxg6 Qb7+
29. f3 Rxe5 30. Ng4 Re1 31. Nf6+ Kf8 32. Rd7 1-0

