1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 ({Once again, we
shall take a look at the alternative} 6... Qa5+ {Now, I would like to show you
another interesting strategy for White.} 7. Nd2 Qa6 8. c4 $1 {Always play this
move when Black wants to exchange the queens.} e6 9. Ngf3 Nh6 10. O-O Nf5 11.
b3 Be7 {Since Black employed a more precise move order, we are unable to
exchange the dark-squared bishops via the g5-square. Nevertheless, we have an
alternative option -} 12. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] White can actually exchange the
bishops via a3. Meanwhile, he gains space on the queenside.} {Taking the pawn
is very dangerous.} Nxh4 ({After} 12... Nd7 13. Ba3 Bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qb6 15. Qc3 {
[%cal Gf1c1,Gb3b4] White can gain even more space on the queenside.
Additionally, exchanging the f5-knight with Nf1-e3 is always an option.}) 13.
Nxh4 Bxh4 14. Ba3 {This is the point. Now, Black cannot castle. After} Be7 15.
Bxe7 Kxe7 16. a5 {Black is completely busted.}) 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Nf3 Qa5+ 9. Nbd2
Qa6 10. c4 $16 Nd7 ({We already know that after} 10... dxc4 11. Nxc4 {Black
cannot complete the development of his kingside. A possible line would be} Bb4+
12. Bd2 ({Even} 12. Ke2 {comes into consideration}) 12... Bxd2+ 13. Nfxd2 Nh6
14. Nd6+ Kf8 15. Qf3 Nd7 16. N2e4 Kg8 17. Rh3 $18 {White is already winning.})
11. b3 Nh6 12. Bxe7 $16 (12. Bxh6 $16 Rxh6 13. O-O dxc4 14. Nxc4 $16 (14. bxc4
$16)) 12... Kxe7 13. Qc3 Qb6 14. O-O Nf5 15. Rfc1 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] Planning
the typical Nf1-e3.} Rhc8 16. Nf1 Ke8 17. cxd5 ({More precise would have been} 
17. Ne3 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Qd8 19. Ng5 $18 {when White is winning by combining
threats on both wings.}) 17... cxd5 18. Qxc8+ Rxc8 19. Rxc8+ Ke7 {Even though
White is still better, the position is already very unclear. At the end, White
managed to win.} 20. Rd1 f6 21. exf6+ Nxf6 22. Rd3 Ng4 23. Rh8 Qa6 24. Rd2 Nf6
25. Rc8 Qb6 26. Rd3 Ng4 27. Rc2 g6 28. Re2 Kf6 29. Ng5 Nxd4 30. Rxd4 Qxd4 31.
Rxe6+ Kg7 32. Re7+ Kf8 33. Ne6+ Kxe7 34. Nxd4 1-0

