576,600,613,611,611,644,824,870,885,920,998,1066,1101]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Ne7 {This is the worst possible
reaction to 7.Bg5. Now, Black cannot complete the development of the kingside.}
8. Ne2 {Although I prefer to develop the knight to f3, this is a perfectly
valid option. Actually, there is no big difference.} Qb6 9. Nd2 Nd7 10. O-O Nf5
({As usual, after} 10... c5 {we have different possibilities. We should always
start calculating the direct approach -} 11. c4 ({Another typical reaction is} 
11. c3 Nf5 12. Nf3 cxd4 13. Nexd4 $1 {Always take with this knight in order to
eliminate the f5-knight.} Nc5 ({We already know that the position arising after
} 13... Nxd4 14. cxd4 Be7 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Qa3+ Ke8 17. Rac1 {is completely
lost for Black.}) 14. Qe2 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Ne4 16. Be3 Be7 17. g3 {[%csl Re4]
[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3] It turns out that the e4-knight is vulnerable. After the
maneuver Ne1-d3, White will start preparing f2-f3.})) 11. c4 $14 dxc4 (11... f6
12. exf6 gxf6 13. Bf4 $14) 12. Nxc4 Qa6 13. Ng3 {An important idea. Besides
eliminating the f5-knight, White wants to open the f-file for his rook.} Nb6 (
13... Nxg3 14. fxg3 Nb6 15. Qf3 $18) 14. b3 $18 {White has a winning advantage
since Black cannot complete the development.} Nxg3 15. fxg3 Nxc4 (15... Nd5 16.
Qf3 f6 17. exf6 gxf6 18. Bxf6) 16. bxc4 Be7 17. Bxe7 Kxe7 18. a4 Rad8 19. Rf4
Rd7 20. Raf1 Ke8 21. Rxf7 Rxf7 22. Qg6 Qxc4 23. Qxf7+ Kd8 24. Qxb7 Qxd4+ 25.
Kh2 Qd7 26. Qb8+ Qc8 27. Rd1+ Ke7 28. Qxa7+ Kf8 29. Rb1 1-0

