{[%evp 0,86,18,34,63,67,61,61,61,44,48,43,43,44,44,44,44,18,20,3,21,-75,-19,
-77,-25,-50,25,25,25,-39,-37,-24,-49,-36,-49,-57,-28,-47,-37,-19,-21,-6,0,-59,
0,-48,-48,-52,0,-5,-15,-19,-8,-33,-35,-24,-43,0,0,-39,3,3,2,0,0,-19,4,-4,31,40,
40,50,52,68,68,47,49,52,10,34,36,34,39,67,40,33,56,2,2]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3.
e5 c5 $5 {This move is objectively less good than 3...Bf5 but it cannot be
refuted and leads to an interesting play. Against this system, I am going to
show you an extremely easy weapon.} 4. dxc5 e6 {Statistically speaking, this
is the most played move. Black makes sure that he will regain the pawn as
quick as possible.} ({In my opinion, however, the most challenging move is} 
4... Nc6 $5 {The idea is that after} 5. Nf3 Bg4 {Black manages to solve the
problem with his light-squared bishop. On the other hand, now he still needs
to work hard in order to regain the c5-pawn.} (5... e6 6. Bd3 {transposes}) 6.
c3 $1 {The most precise move. White is tactically protecting the e5-pawn.} e6 (
{After} 6... Nxe5 $4 7. Nxe5 {White is winning on the spot.}) ({In case of} 
6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 {White should protect the c5-pawn by means of} 8. Be3 {
In this way, we prevent the normal development of the black bishop.
Additionally, by taking the e5-pawn, Black opens the position for our bishop
pair.} Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. c4 $16 {Further opening the position. White has a
big advantage already.} (10. O-O $14)) 7. Be3 {As always, keeping the c5-pawn
is our priority.} a6 {The idea of this move is to take the b5-square under
control.} ({After} 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 {White can go for his typical
reaction -} 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. c4 $16 {with a huge advantage.}) ({The move} 7...
Nxe5 $4 {is dropping a piece after} 8. Qa4+ Nd7 (8... Qd7 9. Bb5 Nc6 10. Qxg4
$18) 9. Qxg4 $18) 8. Nbd2 Nxe5 9. Be2 Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Nf6 11. Bd4 $14 {White's
good central control as well as the queenside extra space provide him with a
slight advantage. 1-0 Jakovenko,D-Kharitonov,A/Moscow 2006} (11. h3 $14)) 5.
Nf3 $1 Bxc5 6. Bd3 $1 {Simple and good! You don't need theoretical knowledge
in order to play this line. As you will see, White is mainly playing for a
control over the dark squares.} Nc6 ({It''s important to point out that after} 
6... Ne7 7. O-O O-O $4 {White can employ a typical tactical idea -} 8. Bxh7+
Kxh7 9. Ng5+ Kg6 10. h4 $1 $18 {The most precise follow up. White is ready to
proceed with Qg4 or Qd3.} ({The alternative is} 10. Qg4 $18 f5 11. Qh4 Rh8 12.
Qg3 f4 13. Qg4 {with a winning attack.})) 7. O-O Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge8g8,Gf7f6]
In this line, Black's counterplay is usually based on the advance ...f7-f6.
Therefore, his next moves will be ...Ng6, ...0-0, and ...f7-f6.} ({The
immediate} 7... f6 {is a bit premature since the black king might be
vulnerable in the centre.} 8. Qe2 $1 fxe5 9. Nxe5 {Black is at crossroads. It
seems that none of the 2 main moves manages to solve the problems.} Nf6 {
This is the most natural continuation.} ({Another important direction is} 9...
Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 11. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gf4g3] Remember this key idea! The bishop
is going to g3 in order to keep the kingside safe.} (11. Bb5+ Kf7 12. Bf4 $14)
11... O-O 12. Bg3 $3 {Now, we can be sure that there will be no problems on
the f-file.} ({The immediate} 12. Nd2 $4 {runs into} Ng4 13. Qh5 Rxf4 $1 $19 {
when Black is winning.}) 12... Kh8 (12... Bd7 13. Nd2 $14) 13. Nd2 $14 {
White enjoys a stable advantage due to his stable blockade on the dark squares.
}) 10. Bf4 $1 O-O 11. Nd2 {It turns out that Black doesn't have convenient way
to remove White's central blockade.} Bd6 ({After} 11... Bd4 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13.
c3 Bb6 {White's advantage is out of question.} 14. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Rc8]}) (11...
Nd4 12. Qd1 $14) 12. Ndf3 Qc7 13. Bg3 Nxe5 ({After} 13... Nh5 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7
15. Ng5+ Kh6 16. Qe3 $18 {[%cal Gg5e6] White is already winning in view of the
threat of Nxe6.}) ({It's very important that after} 13... Nb4 14. a3 Nxd3 15.
cxd3 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] White actually increases his advantage. Since we are
basically fighting for control of the dark-squares, parting with the
light-squared bishop is not an issue for us.}) 14. Nxe5 $16 {Black has no
counterplay whatsoever.}) ({In case of} 7... Nb4 {my preference would be} 8.
Nbd2 {Once again, giving the light-squared bishop away.} ({It goes without
saying that} 8. Be2 {is perfectly natural alternative.}) 8... Nxd3 9. cxd3 Ne7
10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nbd4 O-O 12. Be3 $14 {White has a stable advantage. He wants
to exchange the dark-squared bishops as well as a pair of knights. In this way,
he would reach a fantastic position with queen and knight versus queen and
light-squared bishop. In such a case, Black cannot oppose White's dark-square
strategy.}) 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] White is planning to follow with Nb3.} ({
A natural alternative would be} 8. Bf4 $5 Ng6 ({A typical mistake would be} 
8... O-O $4 {when after the thematic} 9. Bxh7+ Kxh7 10. Ng5+ Kg6 11. Qg4 f5 12.
Qg3 {White has a winning attack. A possible follow up would be} Qe8 13. Nd2 Nd4
14. Rae1 $18 {when White is already winning.}) 9. Bg3 O-O 10. Nbd2 f6 {The
most principled choice. Black is fighting for the important e5-square.} ({
As usual, we are not worried by} 10... Nb4 {White is ready to part with his
light-squared bishop anyway.} 11. Bxg6 ({A decent alternative would be} 11. Nb3
Nxd3 12. cxd3 Bb6 13. Re1 {White is in full control.} ({or} 13. Nfd4)) 11...
hxg6 12. Nb3 Be7 13. h4 {An important move. Besides gaining space, White
prevents his opponent from expanding with ...g6-g5.} Nc6 14. c3 Bd7 15. Re1 Rc8
16. Qd2 {Black does not have counterplay.}) 11. exf6 Qxf6 ({It's important to
answer} 11... gxf6 {with} 12. c4 $14 {Otherwise, Black can build a strong
centre by means of ...e6-e5.} f5 13. h3 f4 14. Bh2 $16 {White is better due to
the vulnerable black king.}) 12. Bxg6 $1 {Remember this thematic move. The
fight revolves around the e5-square.} hxg6 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. c3 $16 {[%csl Rc6,
Re5][%cal Gb3d4] White's positional idea is to exchange the c6-knight by means
of Nd4. In this way, he will get the e5-square under control. Of course, the
exchange of the dark-squared bishops is more than favourable.}) 8... Ng6 ({
Nothing changes} 8... Qc7 $6 9. Nb3 Bb6 10. Re1 Bd7 ({We already know that
after} 10... Ng6 {White can often play} 11. Bxg6 ({Of course, taking
immediately in not necessary. Starting with} 11. Qe2 {is possible as well.} Nb4
12. Bxg6 ({Another highly instructive model game saw} 12. Bd2 $16 Nxd3 13. cxd3
a5 {Just take a look at how White obtained strategically winning position by
executing the right exchanges.} 14. Rac1 Qb8 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 a4 17. Nbd4
Bd7 18. h4 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5] White can actually play on both wings. Black is
strategically lost.}) 12... fxg6 13. c3 Nc6 14. Be3 $16 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 O-O 16.
Nbd4 {Once again, Black is almost lost.}) 11... hxg6 (11... fxg6 12. Be3 O-O
13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. c3 Bd7 15. Qd2 h6 16. Qe3 $14) 12. Bf4 $16 Bd7 13. c3 a5 14.
Nbd4 $16 {As usual happens in such positions, Black does not have any
counterplay.}) 11. c3 Ng6 12. Qe2 $16 ({There is nothing wrong with} 12. Bxg6
fxg6 13. Be3 $16 {getting a classical advantage.})) 9. Nb3 Bb6 ({Even worse is
} 9... Be7 $2 {when Black does not have the potential to put pressure on the
f-file.} 10. Re1 O-O 11. c3 Qc7 ({In case of} 11... f6 {White's most precise
reaction is} 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Nbd4 $16 {Once again, White is
going to win the battle for the important e5-square. Additionally, the black
king is vulnerable.}) ({Let's take a look at what might happen if Black plays
passively -} 11... Bd7 12. Nbd4 $16 Rc8 13. g3 $3 $16 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh2h4,
Gh4h5] This is the point. White makes use of the problematic g6-knight. He is
planning to proceed with h2-h4-h5.} a6 ({Obviously, Black cannot play} 13... f6
{in view of} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Nxe6 $18 ({Even if the e6-pawn was not hanging,
White could have played} 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Bf4 {with a huge positional
advantage.})) 14. h4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd1g4] I prefer this recapture since
White is now ready to put his queen on g4.} Re8 16. Qg4 Bf8 {Eliminating any
counterplay. White does not need to rush.} 17. a4 Ne7 18. h5 Kh8 19. Bg5 $18 {
Black is completely busted. Later on, Fedorchuk converted his advantage in a
flawless way.} Qc7 20. Qf4 Kg8 21. h6 Ng6 22. Qg4 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Qxe5 24. Nf3
Qc7 25. hxg7 Be7 26. Bxh7+ Kxh7 27. g8=Q+ {1-0 Fedorchuk,S-Straver,}) 12. Qe2
$16 f6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Bf4 {Once again, White manages to hold the blockade.})
10. Re1 O-O 11. Bxg6 $1 {The most straightforward solution.} ({An equally
strong alternative is} 11. c3 $1 $14 f6 (11... Qc7 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Be3 $14)
12. exf6 gxf6 ({After} 12... Qxf6 $2 {White's most precise reaction is} 13. Bg5
$3 {forcing the queen to the passive f7-square.} Qf7 14. Be3 $1 $16 {As usual,
White is trying to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} Bc7 15. Ng5 {We can now
see the point behind 13.Bg5} Qf6 16. Qh5 $18 (16. Nxh7) 16... h6 17. Bxg6 $18)
13. Bh6 ({The immediate} 13. c4 $14 {also works quite well.}) 13... Rf7 14. c4
$14 {White should play this move in order to prevent Black from expanding with
...e6-e5.} Nge5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Bf4 Bg4 17. Be2 {White's advantage was
obvious in the game 1-0 Jakovenko,D-Kharitonov,A/Moscow 2006}) 11... fxg6 {
This is the only way to obtain at least some counterplay.} ({After} 11... hxg6
$2 12. Nbd4 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) 12. Be3 h6 13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. c3
g5 15. h3 Bd7 16. Qd2 Rf7 17. Qe3 Qc7 18. Nbd4 $14 {White has a slight but
stable advantage.} *

